Run an auditor-style codebase audit for “documented/implied but not actually wired up” issues.
Goals:
1) Find gaps between docs and reality
2) Find incomplete/missing config and setup expectations
3) Find technically confusing or low-usability implementation choices
4) Fix high-confidence, low-risk issues automatically
5) Provide a plan for anything bigger
Execution requirements:
- Work in parallel passes:
  - Pass A: docs vs code/config mismatch
  - Pass B: config/composition/CI/env completeness
  - Pass C: implementation wiring and UX consistency
- Prioritize by severity: High / Medium / Low
- For each finding, include:
  - What is wrong
  - Evidence (file paths)
  - Why it matters for newcomers/maintainers
  - Proposed fix scope (small/medium/large)
- Apply fixes immediately for small + safe items.
- After edits, run relevant lint/tests for changed areas.
- Never do destructive git operations.
- End with:
  1) “Fixed now” list
  2) “Needs decision” list
  3) “Suggested next PRs” list
Output format:
## Audit Findings
(table: Severity | Area | Issue | Evidence | Impact | Fix Scope)
## Fixed Now
(bulleted list with changed files)
## Remaining Gaps
(bulleted list with proposed approach)
## Validation
(commands run + pass/fail)
